```matlab
x = linspace(-5,5);
y = exp(-x.^2);        % x.^2 squares EACH entry; x^2 would error

x = linspace(0.001,4*pi,1000);
y = sin(x)./x;         % ./ divides entry-by-entry

x = linspace(0.001,2,10000);
y = x.*sin(1./x);      % .* and 1./x are both element-wise
```
With a non-square row vector, `x^2` and `x*x` are invalid (inner dimensions don't match); `x.^2` and `x.*x` are exactly what you want.

```matlab
function [v,i] = taylor_exp(x,toll)
v = 0;
i = 0;
term = 1;
while term >= toll       % keep adding while the term is big enough
    v = v+term;          % accumulate the partial sum
    i = i+1;             % next degree
    term = x^i/factorial(i);  % next Taylor term x^i / i!
end
```
This is the exact body of `taylor_exp.m`: it approximates $e^x$ by $1+x+\frac{x^2}{2!}+\dots$ and stops once a term drops below the tolerance `toll`. `factorial(i)` computes $i!$.
